2 DATE 19 DEC 1914
2 SOUR @S3@
3 PAGE unknown newspaper clipping attached to undertaker's notes
3 DATA
4 TEXT Davenport Loses One of Its Leading Business Men.  Community Shocked by Sudden Death of C. Buck.  Veteran Garage man And Farm Machinery Dealer here 31 Years.  A familiar figure, Charles Henry Buck, beteran garageman and farm implement dealer who wa
5 CONC s well known for his genial smile and kindly greeting, was taken from the community by death Saturday night.
5 CONT
5 CONT Although he had been in poor health for some time, his passing was sudden.  He was on duty at the garage as usual Saturday, and died after supper.
5 CONT
5 CONT For the past 31 years, he has been engaged in the garage business and identified with the business interests of the town over a power of 33 years.  He was a pioneer in the theatre business here, running a movie from 1911 until 1925.
5 CONT
5 CONT Funeral services were held Tuesday afternoon at Christs Lutheran church, conducted by Rev. Henry Dumler, and interment was made in the Davenport cemetery.  Three hymns, "Nearer My God to Thee," "Jesus, Savior, Pilot Me" and "Asleep in Jesus," wer
5 CONC e sung by a quartet composed of Flyd Row, Otto Hasik, Mrs. Frank Johnson and Lena Miller.
5 CONT
5 CONT Business houses were closed during the services.
5 CONT
5 CONT Active pallbearers were Edom Johnson, Everett Lillich, Fred Senften, Frank Johnson, Harold Johnson and Jim Schiller; and honorary pallbearers were Jerry Ringer, J.R. Wolcott, Dr. F.A. Mountford, C.C. McLeese, H.B. Jennings and Dr. C.C.Snowden.
5 CONT
5 CONT Mr. Buck was born October 11, 1883, at Crete, Nebr., and had reached the age of 57 years, one month and 20 days.
5 CONT
5 CONT On December 19, 1914, he married Miss Mary Amy Keim.  They had no children.
5 CONT
5 CONT While in Visalia, Calif., he affiliated with the Methodist church.  He was a member of the masonic lodge and Woodmen of the World.
5 CONT
5 CONT He is survived by his wife; mother, Mrs. Mina Berkey of Davenport; and two sisters.  Mrs. Austin Skinner of Buffalo, Mont, and Mrs. Frank Rogers of Seattle, Wash.  His father, Jess, and sister, Mrs. Walter Skinner, and a brother, Claude, precede
5 CONC d him in death.
