0 @N1@ NOTE
1 CONC Worked as a pumper on rice farms in Devils Bluff, Arkansas.  Moved family to Geary after mother Laura Ann Buck died.  His nephew, Loren Buck (son of Elijah Enoch) said, "Amos did barbering and farming after this marriage (to Anna Ronie).  I rememb
1 CONC er that many Sunday mornings while Amos and his family lived with his mother, Laura, that his four nephews: Leo, Bernard, Arden and I would have Uncle Amos cut our hair in his yard.  He sat us on a kitchen chair with an apron tied around our necks
1 CONC .  He did this free of charge.  When Grandma Buck (Laura Ann) died, in 1918, as previously mentioned, the estate sold the home to George and Daisy Buck and the Amos Buck family, which included the first four children, moved to Geary, Oklahoma.
0 @N2@ NOTE
1 CONC She grew up believing her name was Annie Roney Kirby.  When applying for a birth certificate sometime after 1940, Annie found that her given name at birth had actually been Sarah Laura.  However, the 1910 census lists her as "Anna."
1 CONT
0 @N3@ NOTE
1 CONC Disappeared in 1946, just before irregularities involving his sale of insurance policies were discovered.
0 @N4@ NOTE
1 CONC George fought in World War I and was wounded and gassed.  Shell-shocked for the rest of his life, he died in a soldiers home in Sheridan, Wyoming.
0 @N5@ NOTE
1 CONC Robert at one time was granted a 160 acre homestead near Danville, Illinois by the Federal Land Office.
1 CONT
1 CONT Robert's sister, Hannah Kirby, married Robert's first wife Phoebe's brother Samuel Graham.
1 CONT
1 CONT Robert Phares Kirby was born 6 November 1812 in Warren Co., Ohio, the son of James and Sarah (Phares) Kirby.  He married Phoebe Graham 24 January 1833 in Warren Co., Ohio.  In 1845 he came to Dewitt Co. Illinois and lived near Waynesville and boug
1 CONC ht 160 acres of land in Section 3 of Barnett Township.  From 1850 to 1858 the land records in the Clinton, Illinois courthouse show that he bought and sold several tracts of land, some of these deals apparently involving relatives (Allen Phares, S
1 CONC amuel Graham, Jonathan Graham and Robert H. Phares).
1 CONT
1 CONT According to one story, by 1858 he had sold most of his holdings and with $8,000 in gold, he started for Kansas with a Mr. Gandy and wife from Kenney, Illinois.  He told his wife Phoebe that he would buy a farm and then send for her and the childr
1 CONC en.  He never returned, but (according to reliable evidence handed down in Phoebe's  family) instead ran off with Mr. Gandy's wife to San Antonio, Texas where he raised another family of four girls and two boys, dying in that vicinity January 8th
1 CONC , 1897.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alice Elenor Kirby, granddaughter of Robert P. Kirby by his second wife, Tamson Currie, tells a different story.  Robert lived in Osawatomie, Kansas and engaged in raising thoroughbred race horses and just before the Civil War he started for Texa
1 CONC s with a number of horses to buy a ranch.  He had joined a wagon-train for this journey and while on the way the wagon-train was attacked by Indians or outlaws.  A Mr. Currie and his wife Tamson were members of this party and Mr. Currie was kille
1 CONC d in the attack.
1 CONT
1 CONT The family in Texas never knew about Robert's family in Dewitt Co., Illinois.  John V. Kirby, great-grandson of Robert P. and Phoebe (Graham) Kirby, spoke with Alice, and she related that she had many times heard her mother, Annie Jane Scott (marr
1 CONC ied to Robert Gilbert Kirby, son of Robert P. and Tamson Kirby) tell the story of the Indian attack on the wagon-train, and that after Mr. Currie was killed, Robert and Tamson were married and lived for approximately seven years in Denton County
1 CONC , in the northern part of Texas, before later going on down to San Antonio.
1 CONT
1 CONT The 1880 census for Bexar Co., Texas lists Robert Phares Kirby with wife Tamson and seven children living on a farm about 20 miles southwest of San Antonio.  The land records in the courthouse in San Antonio show that he bought and sold several fa
1 CONC rms and several lots in and around San Antonio between 1876 and 1890.  He appears to have retained possession of 117 acres near the southwest corner of Bexar Co.
1 CONT
1 CONT Alice indicated to John V. Kirby in 1973 that sometime after 1890 Robert deserted his second family and spent his last years following race horses and gambling on them all over Texas.  His burial place is unknown, but Alice believes he is buried i
1 CONC n the old Benton cemetary which is in Atascosa Co., south of Bexar Co. in Texas.  Robert was father of 17 children with an age difference of 44 years between the first and the last.
1 CONT
0 @N6@ NOTE
1 CONC Phoebe's brother, Samuel Graham, married Hannah Kirby, the sister of Phoebe's husband, Robert Phares Kirby.
0 @N7@ NOTE
1 CONC John served in Company L, 4th Cavalry Illinois along with his uncle, Joseph Collins Kirby.  They were with General U.S. Grant at the battle of Shiloh.
1 CONT
1 CONT John married Sarah Barnett, who was the sister of John Irwin Barnett, who was married to John's sister Mary Matilda Kirby.
1 CONT
0 @N8@ NOTE
1 CONC John was the brother of Sarah Barnett, who was married to Mary's brother, John Devolhay Kirby.
0 @N9@ NOTE
1 CONC James inherited a 192 acre farm in SEction 34 of Clear Creek Township, Warren County, Ohio on the death of his father, but had no legal title till his mother's death in 1847.
0 @N11@ NOTE
1 CONC Died when small from an accidental shooting.
0 @N12@ NOTE
1 CONC Served in Company L of the 4th Illinois Cavalry in the Civil War.  Buried in Pleasant Valley Cemetary near Kenney, Illinois.
0 @N13@ NOTE
1 CONC Richard owned 450 acres in New Hanover Township, Burlington County, New Jersey, in 1720s.  Built sawmill in Cookstown in 1732 and ran it until he died.
1 CONT
0 @N14@ NOTE
1 CONC Ann sold 560 acres in New Hanover Township for 392 Pounds in 1755.
0 @N15@ NOTE
1 CONC Recompense's name appears on the Dartmouth Town Records in 1684, 1686 and 1695.  He moved to Burlington County, New Jersey in 1698.  At his death, his will disposed of 500 acres of land to his children.
0 @N16@ NOTE
1 CONC Probably came to America with his brother Joseph in 1635, to Lynn, MA.  Lived there in 1636 and with others began settlement of Sandwich, MA in 1637.  He appears in 1643 on a list of those able to bear arms.  Member of the Puritan Church of Sandwi
1 CONC ch.  In 1651 was censored for non-attendance at public worship (Sandwich Puritan Church known as one of the most bigoted and intolerant in the Colony).
