1 CONC "Joseph Preston Yadon ran away from home at an early age.  When he was 12 years old, he enlisted as a drummer in the English Army and came to America shortly before the Revolution.  he served under Burgoyne and was captured with him by the America
1 CONC n Army.  After his capture, he joined the continental troops and served two years as a drump major under Captains John Carney, Tipton, Capman and Cherry, and Colonel Joseph Crockett.  he was in General Clark's expedition to the Falls of Ohio.  H
1 CONC e enlisted at Martinsburg, Berkley Co., West Virginia in 1779 and was discharged in 1781.  From 1832 to his death he drew a pension of $24 quarterly.
1 CONT
1 CONT "Joseph and Susaannah Mary Yadon resided at or near Tazwell and Rutledge, Tenn.  At one time their Post Office was Haynes, Tenn.  Many of their original documents were signed with a mark, and the name is spelled in various ways - Yaden, Yadon, Yad
1 CONC er on the pension papers."  - Grainger Co. and It's People.
1 CONT
1 CONT "Another story handed down from early descendants says that after Joseph had married and was living in Virginia in the late 1790s, he was left a large inheritance from an uncle, a brother of Betsy Proctor, Sir William Proctor, who was a wealthy su
1 CONC rgeon in Ireland.  the property was called the Silverdale Estate.  The story goes that Joseph was never able to return to Ireland to claim this estate, and after 100 years it was returned to the crown.  However, in the 1930s a letter was receive
1 CONC d by Nina Yadon Tucker of Richland, Missouri from two attorneys in Ireland that the estate was still there.  But by this time Yadon had so many heirs that there was no way this estate could ever be settled."  from Grainger County and It's People.
1 CONT
