1 CONC 1886 Biographical and Historical Record of Wayne and Appanoose Counties, Iowa
1 CONT Chicago: Inter-State Pub. Co.,
1 CONT
1 CONT George Gallaher, one of the pioneers of Appanoose County, was born in Warren County, Indiana, near Williamsport, January 7, 1828, a son John W. and Hannah (Schemerhorn) Gallaher.  When he was quite young his father died, and about the age of nin
1 CONC e years he was left motherless, and therefore has little knowledge of his parents.  He lived with his guardian until about sixteen years of age, when he started out to commence the battle of life for himself, and worked on farms in his native Stat
1 CONC e until twenty-one years old.  Being charmed with the glowing descriptions of the West he resolved to visit Iowa, and accordingly, in the fall of 1849, started on his journey.  He remained in Iowa during the winter, and the following spring return
1 CONC ed to Indiana, but soon after came again to Iowa, and entered 160 acres of land near Unionville, Appanoose County.  Three months later he sold it, and in September of the same year bought a claim in the western part of Taylor Township.  This he al
1 CONC so sold and then purchased 160 acres near the present site of the Missouri, Iowa & Nebraska Railroad depot, on section 5.  In 1864 he bought the farm where he now lives, on section 6, which contains eighty acres of choice land, marking 240 acres
1 CONC , all under improvement.  In addition to farming he is quite extensively engaged in stock-raising, making a specialty of cattle and hogs.  He is an enterprising man, and from a poor orphan boy has come to be one of the prosperous farmers of Appano
1 CONC ose County.  He has held various official positions in the township, among others that of supervisory, trustee and assessor.  He was the first man in the township to hold the latter office.  Mr. Gallaher was married in 1856 to Mahala Buck, a nativ
1 CONC e of Missouri (1).   She died November 6, 1883.  They had a family of seven children - Thomas J., of Nebraska; Dora E., wife of D.J. Funkhouse; Jesse M. of Seward County, Nebraska; Cora C., Charles E., George E. and John W.
1 CONT
1 CONT (1)  Wrong - they were married 3 April 1853, per Early Marriage Records of Appanoose County, 1847-1900.  Also, Mahala was born in Michigan, not Missouri.
1 CONT
1 CONT In various censuses and other documents, George's last name is spelled variously, "Gallaher", "Gallagher", and "Gollaher".  Since George himself used the latter, I have done so as well.
